PROBLEM 1

PART 1 Q1 Construct a scatterplot with median age on the x-axis and the percentage of people who voted for Trump on the y-axis. Describe the relationship you see.

election2016 <- read.csv("election2016.csv")

ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(x=medianAge, y=percentTrump), data=election2016)

state,county,FIPS,percentTrump,hsGrad,collegeGrad,poverty,unemployment,population,medianAge,femalePct

PART 1 Q2 Fit a simple linear regression model where the response is the percentage of people who voted for Trump and the predictor is median age. Construct residual diagnostic plots of that fit. Do there appear to be any assumption violations?

election2016fit <- lm(percentTrump ~ medianAge, data=election2016)
autoplot(election2016fit)

The residual vs fitted trend line does not appear to be too straihgt and the QQ-plot data points seem to follow a slight arch

PART 1 Q3 Use a Box-Cox plot to determine whether a transformation of the response variable could improve the model fit. If the plot suggests a transformation, fit the model with that transformation and comment on the residual diagnostic plots for that model. Does it make sense to do a transformation?

gg_boxcox(election2016fit)

election2016fit <- lm(percentTrump ^ 1.92 ~ medianAge, data=election2016)
autoplot(election2016fit)

The residual vs fitted trend line does not appear to have improved while the QQ-plot very slightly imporved but not enough to keep the transfromation. So no it does not make sense.

PART 1 Q4 Check the model summary for the model in part 2. What percent of the variability in voting rates is explained by median age? (Reference specific output).

election2016fit <- lm(percentTrump ~ medianAge, data=election2016)
summary(election2016fit)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = percentTrump ~ medianAge, data = election2016)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -52.417  -9.298   2.517  10.984  33.588 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 21.92201    2.15947   10.15   <2e-16 ***
## medianAge    1.02323    0.05309   19.27   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 14.87 on 3111 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.1067, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1064 
## F-statistic: 371.5 on 1 and 3111 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

In this model, 10.64% of the variability can be explained by median age.

PART 1 Q5 Is median age a significant predictor of the voting rates? (Reference specific output).

Yes, because the p-value for medianAge is <2e-16 which tells you the multiplier is signifcant. Also for a single variable, it can explain 10% variabilty.

PART 1 Q6 Interpret the coefficient for median age in the context of the data.

For every 1 year increase in the median age, percentTrump increases by 1.02323.

Construct a scatterplot matrix for the variables in this data. Describe/discuss any associations you see with the response variable.

ggscatmat(election2016)
## Warning in ggscatmat(election2016): Factor variables are omitted in plot

The correlation between Percent Trump and unemployment is not weak to moderate at -0.28. There is a fairly weak negative correlation between unemployment rate and percent Trump (The higher the unemployment, the percent Trump). Likewise, population has a weak to moderate negative correlation with percent Trump (more unemployment correlated with a higher percent Trump). The correlation between medianAge and percent Trump is slightly postive moderate at .13.
